> I was under the impression the "map" is defined by the tap locations along
> the pot in the "AFM"


No, that's just one signal, a variable voltage to the ECU depending on where
the vane is positioned.  I guess each ECU for various models/years has a
different "map."

> >The "ideal 14.7:1 ratio or 0.450 volts" is NOT ideal for air cooled VWs.
> >I try for no greater than 13:1 idle or cruise. Sorry but your guess as to
> >what 13:1 equals on your set up is as good as mine. I would set it at
0.625
> >volts and look at the plugs and exhaust color. Better rich than lean.

> > >While it's true that, for engine longevity, running richer is better
than
> > >running leaner, I'm not sure your practice here has any real affect.
When
> > >the engine's warmed up the ECU looks to run the mixture right around
the
> > >ideal ratio, which is right around .5 volts for a properly functioning
O2
> > >sensor.  So, if you unhook your O2 sensor, fool around with the idle
air
> > >mixture to run "rich" and then reconnect your O2 sensor, I'm not sure
you
> > >accomplish much.
>
> Sorry I thought that this was non closed loop such as a 1977 and Mark was
> using  an Ox detector to set up the open loop air fuel ratio.

You're right about that.  I was thinking of my '81 which has the O2 as
standard equipment.
